MUSHROOM POISONING - RUSSIA (VOLGOGRAD, VORONEZH)
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
[1]
Date: 13 Jul 2000 13:01:16 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: AP Online, story filed 13 Jul 2000 5:55 AM EDT [edited]

Poisonous Russian Mushrooms Kill 11
-------------------------------------
MOSCOW (AP) -- Toxic mushrooms have killed 11 people and sickened 150
others this month [July] in the southern Russian town of Voronezh,
officials said Thursday. One child was among the dead and 18 children among
those injured in the last 12 days, said Alexander Zalyotov, spokesman for
the Emergency Situations Ministry. Zalyotov said sales of wild mushrooms
have been banned in the town 300 miles south of Moscow, and in the
surrounding region.
Gathering wild mushrooms for pickling or soups is a popular summer pastime
for Russians, but often results in poisoning outbreaks that can fell entire
families. As little as a single mushroom cap can be fatal if it's one of
the more toxic varieties. Officials sometimes also blame poisoning on
mushrooms growing in heavily contaminated soil.
